<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911015-0041</DOCNO><DOCID>911015-0041.</DOCID><HL>   Oryx Energy, Amoco   To Eliminate Jobs</HL><DATE>10/15/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8</SO><CO>   AN ORX</CO><MS>ENERGY (ENE)</MS><IN>OIL-INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)OIL-SECONDARY (OIS)PETROLEUM (PET)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)RESTRUCTURINGS, RECAPITALIZATION (RCN)ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>COLORADO (CO)ILLINOIS (IL)NORTH AMERICA (NME)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   DALLAS -- Oryx Energy Co. said it would eliminate close to1,000 jobs in line with the closing of two regional officesand a previously announced restructuring. The companycurrently has about 2,600 employees world-wide, of which2,500 are based in the U.S.   Separately, Amoco Corp. said it would shift operations ofits Denver exploration unit to Houston, eliminating 65 jobs.An additional 90 workers will be given an opportunity totransfer to the oil company's Houston offices.</LP><TEXT>   A number of energy concerns recently outlined such stepsas cost-cutting, consolidations, work force reductions andasset sales in preparation of rising costs partially relatedto bringing older facilities into compliance with federal andstate environmental statutes, and lower oil prices as moreoil comes into the market.   Oryx, an exploration and production company, said it wouldclose regional offices in Houston and Oklahoma City,consolidating operations at its Dallas headquarters. Oryxsaid the elimination of the 1,000 jobs would result from theconsolidation, staff reductions at its Dallas headquartersand from the sale of assets.   Amoco also recently announced cuts and consolidations thatwould result in a number of layoffs, including a number ofcuts resulting from the closure of an outdated refinery inCasper, Wyo.</TEXT></DOC>